# The built documents. THE MARKDOWN IS THE SOURCE; the PDF is an artifact of it, of the
# binary (the reference chapters are printed from the program) and of a browser.
#
# The USER-FACING PDFs ARE TRACKED. tools/build-docs.sh makes docs/altairsim-manual.pdf and
# docs/altairsim-devguide.pdf, and they are versioned deliverables: they ship in the
# distribution zip beside the binary, and a fresh clone should carry the manual a reader can
# open without a pandoc-and-a-browser toolchain to build it. So they are committed on purpose
# (regenerate and re-commit them when the docs change), and NOT listed here.
#
# The line that is NOT ours to track is the SCANNED REFERENCE MANUALS in reference/ (below):
# vendor datasheets, tens of MB each, and burned into this repo's history twice already. That
# is the "no PDFs in the reference directory" rule -- our documentation is fine, their scans
# are not. The intermediate HTML the browser prints from stays an artifact too.
docs/*.html
.altairsim_history

# Disk/tape images are large and usually not ours to redistribute.
# Commit them deliberately with `git add -f` if a test genuinely needs one.
*.dsk
*.DSK
*.cas
*.img

# disks/ IS AN ALLOWLIST, and it is deliberately the other way round from everything
# above (Patrick, 2026-07-13: "the only files we need tracked in the /disks directory
# are the TOML files").
#
# What lives there is somebody else's: 20 MB of CP/M images, vendor ReadMes, and the
# .PRN listings that come with them. A denylist would have to guess at every extension
# a future download brings, and a single `git add -A` on a miss puts 20 MB in history
# forever -- which has already happened once in this repo, with reference/, and had to
# be rewritten out. So NOTHING under disks/ is tracked unless it is named here.
#
# Three kinds of thing earn a line:
#   - the machine files, which ARE ours;
#   - one README per directory, saying where to download the images (deramp.com) and
#     how to run them -- so a fresh clone knows exactly what it is missing and why;
#   - the .ASM listings the BOARDS WERE BUILT FROM. Those are first-hand period sources
#     under DESIGN.md 0.1 and are cited by path in docs/boards/*.md. Losing them would
#     mean the 88-DCDD's register map, its timing, and the Tarbell's grounded-E30
#     finding all cite a file that is not there.
disks/**
!disks/**/
!disks/**/*.toml
!disks/**/README.md
!disks/mits-88dcdd/cpm22/buffered/BIOS.ASM
!disks/mits-88dcdd/cpm22/buffered/BOOT.ASM
!disks/mits-88dcdd/cpm22/8mb/BIOS.ASM
!disks/mits-88dcdd/cpm22/8mb/BOOT.ASM
!disks/mits-88dcdd/cpm22/8mb/FORMAT8M.ASM
!disks/mits-88mds/cpm22/BIOS.ASM
!disks/mits-88mds/cpm22/BOOT.ASM
!disks/tarbell-sd/cpm22/buffered/BIOS (1).ASM

# Scanned manuals and datasheets. Same reasoning as the disk images, and then
# some: they are enormous (the 88-DCDD manual alone is 52 MB) and they are not
# ours. They are the SOURCE the boards were built from, not part of the build --
# keep them here on disk, cite them by filename in the code, and let
# docs/sources.md say where each one came from. See [altair-hardware-sources].
#
# This was decided once, and then a `git add -A` put 83 MB of them in history
# anyway; that history has been rewritten out. If you find yourself typing
# `git add -f reference/...`, you are about to do it a third time.
#
# The ONE exception, allowlist-style like disks/ above: the *.md files here are
# OURS -- distilled, text-only emulation references written FROM the scans, each
# citing its source PDF by filename. "Our documentation is fine, their scans are
# not." Those are tracked; the scans themselves stay ignored.
reference/*
!reference/*.md
